debriefing_1: How people try to find a fit with others and what they look for when searching for a partner
strategy_text: I have used several online dating sites, and take a similar approach on each. I first browse profile photos to find females that meet my physical attractiveness criteria. I then more carefully review these profiles to ensure a personality and interest match and try to decipher what type of person they are. If I find them both physically and personally attractive, I will contact them in hopes of receiving a response. Of the profiles I look at, I may contact approximately one quarter of them.  When I am contacted first, I typically do not respond too frequently. I often find that the women who contact me are not people I would be interested in. /  / I actually have not been able to meet any of my contacts in person. Conversations typically fall off before reaching that point. However, I would be willing to meet with someone who, after speaking to them several times, I feel they would have potential as a romantic partner.
change_strategy_text: In the beginning, I had slightly higher standards. Once I contacted all of my "ideal" candidates, I then took on more realistic standards. However, I would not sacrifice what I am looking for to simply get a date. On the whole, I have employed the same strategy throughout my time online dating because I feel it is effective in helping me identify women who I find attractive and feel would be a suitable partner for me. /  / I have tried out different profile descriptions and messages based on research on what has worked for others. However, I have not found that any type of profile statement or message is any more effective than another.
success_def: Online dating success, to me, would mean finding someone with whom a long-term relationship is possible. I would have met someone who has the potential to make me happy in a committed relationship.
suc_tactics: I try to be selective about who to contact and I am attentive to profile information that is either attractive or unattractive to me. I do not waste time on individuals with whom I dont think I am compatable or with whom I could not see myself in a long-term relationship.

strategy_text: I signed up for many different dating sites, so I could get a good idea of what was out there, and what sites had the best quality men.  Unfortunately, Plenty of Fish has been the most terrible and disappointing site of them all, only reeling in scum bags.  I mostly looked for decent men, with morals, around my age, and they had to have a spiritual nature and relationship with God.  If not, I did not contact them or talk with them.  If the men had more then two children, that was a no go also, as I have three and it would just get to be too many... / I generally only talked to a handful of people at once, but usually just tried to focus on one person at a time, because it is way too time consuming to try and talk to more then one at once.  I did not meet any men in person until I really felt they put effort into texting me, calling me and getting to know me.  If they pushed to fast to meet, and didn't want to open up emotionally or put in any effort, I got rid of them immediately.  That's a sign of a player and a guy who only wants to hook up. /  / Eharmony has also been a huge disappointment (for other reasons) in the sense that, they choose my matches for me, and I haven't had one suitable match that I was actually attracted to in the 7 months that I have been on that site. /  / Generally, I only talk to about 1-2% of the men who message me on any of the dating sites I've been on.  I know what I want, and most of them don't match it at all.
change_strategy_text: I definitely had to learn the hard way, after going out with a couple guys who just ended up being complete losers and scumbags.  I learned that if a guy pushes too fast or won't put in effort, they are only out for one thing.  Although, a few still play the game so well, that it's really hard to tell.  I also learned to watch for other red flags among these potential dates, and at the first sign of something I don't like, I end it.  I learned to just cut my losses and move on before I wasted too much time on another complete loser.  For example, one guy I was dating was so cheap, he was inviting me out and making me pay for my own dinner.  I ended the relationship due to him being so cheap.  I also will cut men off if they talk nasty, or talk to me about other women they find attractive.

musthaves-6: Must have the same political preferences as me
lazy, and too friendly with an ex gf, wife etc...
success_def: I define success as finding a long term partner, and a committed romantic relationship.
suc_tactics: I think screening out the men at the first sign of a red flag will cut losses and save a lot of wasted time.  I have a list of things I will not tolerate, I learned the hard way that it's no use to date someone who does things that are not compatible with who I am  and my morals and beliefs, as it will never work out.

I have been in several long term relationships that have not satisfied me physically. Therefore, I like to take multiple women out. I am not interested in dating "sluts" I look for successful, independent women that understand I do not want a commitment and I am primarily looking for friendship that has physical benefits. They have to be able to hold up a conversation and that is why I enjoy finding women online, they cannot use their looks to hook me in, they have to have independent thought. I use this strategy to filter out women I do not want to interact with. Furthermore, they have to be open to talking about sex. If they aren't open to it, then I am also not interested. It takes some time, but they come around more often then not.
change_strategy_text: I used to be coy about what I wanted with women, but I found that being straight up with them, the ones I wanted to spend time with were more appreciative of being up front and honest. Therefore, I stopped "beating around the bush" and told the women I have met exactly what I am looking for. It makes for some awkward conversations when I am weeding out the ones I don't want.
success_def: Going on many dates that end up in friendship and casual sex
suc_tactics: Being open and honest about exactly what I want, you have to be willing to put in the time talking to a lot of people, but there are many people out there looking for the same thing.

debriefing_1: How we view and deal with online dating?
strategy_text: I use both apps with an open mind. I guess age has a lot to do with this approach: I have learned that there's no suck thing as the perfect partner out there, just regular people trying to do their best or a handful that don't even want to even try. So I browse around, read the profiles and look at pictures and when I see someone that piqued my interest, I get in touch. I think it's easier for a woman to make the first contact, a way to break the ice and also put the guy in a "safe" place where he can show himself more easily since he think he does have to do much to impress since you're (at least in theory) already interested. Sometimes work, sometimes it does not, you meet a lot of people that are not what they portrait online, so the hardest thing for me is to find out the fakes and leave them behind. In any case, I don't that myself or this search too serious... Or, not serious at all. I have met good people and keep using it daily, but I also keep my eyes open in the real world: if I see someone that I think it's interesting in a coffee shop or at the bookstore, I have no problem letting them know I'm interested. So, open mind, doesn't take online dating too serious and enjoy whatever happens.
change_strategy_text: In the early 2000's I used match.com and I was totally different back them. I did not approach the guys at all, just let my inbox fill up and would choose the ones I believe had some dating potential. It was not fun seeing all these people that had nothing in common with me wanting some attention, while the ones I wanted were not. I was silly and proud and didn't even consider getting in touch myself. I think that I took this process very serious. I have learned to lighten up since.
musthaves-7: Has a job that makes him happy and proud
msg_time-TEXT: Depends on the person I'm in touch with. It can be 24/hrs or weeks.
success_def: Meeting someone that I can relate to, have fun, a good laugh, enjoy some time together that's pleasurable for both of us, be it for a couple of hours or weeks or months, that's success to me.
suc_tactics: Don't expect too much, have an open mind, don't take it too serious and enjoy it for what it is.

debriefing_1: How people use online dating to find their partners
strategy_text: I heard about Bumble from one of my girlfriends that had had success meeting men on there. I decided it couldn't hurt to sign up. If nothing else, it might be fun, and I had nothing to lose. So I signed up for the site, and I was interested immediately. There was a surprising number of guys from my area on there, some of whom I knew! So I started looking through profiles just to see who I knew and what they would say. After reading some of them and scanning a few women from the area too to see what my competition was like, I went back and added to my profile. I wanted to make myself unique and different from the other girls out there. I was genuine and honest with everything I put, but I tried to let my personality come through. It's been working well for me so far. I usually get a message from at least one guy per week, and I message a few myself, if they look interesting to me. I look out for anyone who sounds like a player or too arrogant. I don't want someone who has a lot of baggage, although I am open to a divorced guy. Just no drama with the ex-wife, please. Once I get a message or send one, I chat back and forth with the guy for a few days. I usually get him to send me a few pics, in case his profile one isn't real. Then we exchange numbers and text for a bit. When I'm comfortable and if we seem to be clicking, I'll suggest meeting in a public place for a date. From there on out, it's mostly like dating in real life.
change_strategy_text: Well, I haven't been online dating for THAT long, but I do feel like I have a better idea what to look for in men's profiles now. For example, if they say they're interested in "average" sized women, they really mean they want someone in personal-trainer like shape. I tend to skip them. If they have really long profiles, I avoid that too. They tend to be self-important and talk non-stop about themselves. I also tend to be more direct in my responses. I mean, I'm flirty too, but I don't really hint at things. I say what I mean, because I don't want anyone to claim that they misunderstood me.
success_def: For me, online dating success will mean meeting a few people and having a great time on my dates. I don't necessarily have to find the right one online for it to be a success to me. I just want to have a good time and a fun experience. If I learn something and laugh, I think that's good enough. If I meet the right one, even better.
suc_tactics: Basically just being myself and being up front about what I want and who I am. I don't lie to anyone or try to lead them on. I let my sense of humor out. I make fun of the awkwardness and don't take it too seriously to begin with. If you do, you get too nervous to enjoy yourself and that makes the other person not enjoy it either. I am always careful about knowing who I am meeting and going somewhere public. Even if the date goes well, I don't go anywhere alone with them till we've been out several times. That's just safety and common sense.

debriefing_1: I thought it was about online dating.  How we see ourselves and what we want out of others.
strategy_text: I start off by reading profiles.  I usually prefer a pic because if everyone is honest, it does matter.  I read the profiles and look for something different, something interesting.  Most people write the same, tired, boring cliches that everyone else writes.  "I love long walks on the beach".  Blech.  "I like to have fun."  Really.  Are there people out there who don't like to have fun?  "I want a girl who can be equally comfortable in an evening gown as well as a pair of jeans."  (eye roll)  "I want someone down to earth."  "No baggage".  I bypass all of those immediately because it tells me that they aren't creative, they are boring, they don't know what they want, and not a thing about them sparks my interest.  Also, every single person on this earth has some kind of "baggage", if we are to use their definition.  OH, "someone who doesn't have daddy issues".  Insulting people right off the bat..what a catch! /  / In the photos, I look to see who they cropped out, (usually there's strands of long hair still in the pic - hilarious), or I see if these "no gold diggers" and "want someone who is down to earth" have parked themselves in front of someone's expensive house, car, or are wearing flashy clothes/jewelry.  That's a massive red flag right there. /  / Honestly, this weeds out about 99.9% of the people on these sites. /  / I have found a few profiles where the person looked alright, and their profile was very different, hilarious, and definitely got me intrigued.  I've written to some of those people, and we've had great conversations back and forth. /  / Sometimes, despite all of that, the person wants to rush to talk on the phone.  Always asking for a phone number within one reply.  NOPE!  Or the ones who write this great profile and then reply with a single sentence/statement.  Bye. /  / I'm very choosy.  With looks, they don't have to be an Adonis, I just have to like how they look.  With their profile, I'm VERY picky.  If they can't spell, I'm done.  If they are unwilling to communicate using email or messages, are too pushy about talking on phone or meeting up after their one sentence reply, I'm done.  If they can't engage in a conversation, what on earth is the point?  If their profile is bland, neutral, boring...what's the point?  This is their time to present the best side of them, and it's boring?  What does that tell me I'll get in the future?  Boring. /  / They don't have to be a dare devil, visited every place on earth, etc, they just have to be INTERESTING!  Put some effort in to it.  I spend a lot of time weeding people out, and I spend a whole lot of time deleting stupid messages that I get from idiots who clearly are not actually interested in a relationship.  They should be on Tinder and swiping left or right for all the care they take to "get to know" someone.   /  / Really, online dating is like real life.  There's a lot of undesirable people on there.  The good thing is, you can weed them out from the comfort of your home without spending all that time finding out the hard way.
change_strategy_text: No, my strategies have not changed.  I was pretty detailed in the last page, and my strategy saves me a lot of time.  I'm not going to get dressed up, go out, spend money just to sit with someone who can't hold a conversation.  Or one who clearly wants to move too fast...no.  Gross.   /  / As I said, it is like real life.  You have to wade through people you absolutely do not want to hang out with at all to find a few gems.  This way, however, you are saving a whole lot of time.

strategy_text: Not including the current relationship that I am in (we met in person), I have met my past few dating partners on dating sites in spite of the notorious idea of "hook-up" culture surrounding the sites. However, the "hook-up" aspect had always caused gray areas of uncertainty in those relationships and put strains on them, as they would start as casual flings before becoming serious (save for my most recent ex boyfriend, who continued to meet women off these sites behind my back in spite of the two of us establishing a commitment of monogamy in our relationship). /  / I never found my partners with the intent to seek out a romantic partner, but unfortunately when I had been seeking out people to pass the time with in order to "get over" a prior relationship. I am very selective with whom I choose to give out my number to and who I then meet up in person with, so I have to feel a sort of connection with them before choosing to meet them in person. Usually in these instances, I send them the initial message to express my interest/start a conversation and see where it leads to.
change_strategy_text: After my third failed relationship, I figured that it was best to look at the way I was using online dating as sort of an unhealthy coping mechanism because I was so afraid of formulating natural relationships, and even more afraid of being alone. I was in a sense using these men as a way of making myself feel better, and sometime forcing a relationship out of it. It wasn't fair for me or for them to waste our times that way. So I kept my profiles, but I never really took it seriously. If people messaged me, I would try to carry on a conversation but I wouldn't meet up with people, give out my phone number, or really get too attached. It became more of a joke, really. /  / I met my current boyfriend when I wasn't out looking for one. I was reeling months and months after my last relationship (who I had met on Bumble after breaking up with my ex that I met on Tinder......) had ended due to his infidelity after moving for work, and during our relationship. I was trying hard to be happy alone and discover what it is I enjoyed alone, and started working at a theatre part time while aimlessly swiping on sites simply for the company. I met my partner while he was working a shift with me too, and I decided to not continue my use of these sites.

strategy_text: I primarily use Tinder these days because I mostly rely on online dating for casual relationships/friends with benefits, and Tinder gives me the kind of platform that I want; where I can easily see how someone physically looks as well as brief information about them. I can swipe left or right, and engage in conversation if they pick me as well. If all goes well, I will exchange my phone number or Skype username with the person, and we'll take it from there. I'm not very big on serious and committed dating, so I tend to stay away from some of the bigger online dating websites because they have too much information in one place that I don't really care about right off the bat. I like to keep it simple: swipe left or right, engage in a conversation, move the conversation away from the Tinder app and into texts or Skype messages.
change_strategy_text: In the beginning, I was appalled by Tinder because I thought the idea of casual dating or just hook-ups were flat out wrong. I used a lot of the older, more established websites like OkCupid and Plenty of Fish, where you fill out an extensive profile and find other people with extensive profiles, but I found that I rarely kept a good conversation going on those websites. I still check on those sites periodically, but I realized that I wasn't interested in long-term, romantic, committed relationships like most other people on OkCupid, so I gave Tinder a shot because it was more casual and there wasn't as much pressure. So, I definitely moved my online dating perspective away from finding a happy, fairy-tale romance and focused more on casual dating opportunities.
dealbreaker-4: People who are too preoccupied with themselves
om_7_TEXT: My primary reasons for an online meeting are to make sure we get along well and that we can carry a conversation. If I can't carry a conversation with someone online, then I know I won't be able to carry a conversation with them in person so I know not to pursue it anymore.  /  / It also saves money to get to know each other via Skype first before wasting money on a date that might not work out.  /  / It also helps to make sure both of us can see each other beforehand, just so we can be comfortable in person and there's no awkwardness because we've already seen each other "face-to-face" through Skype.
success_def: I think online dating success is finding one person who you really hit it off with. They don't necessarily have to be your soulmate, just someone that you really enjoy talking to on a regular basis. suc_tactics: I have found that being real and honest from the start has led me to success. No fake compliments or fake pick-up lines to try and woo the other person; just being me from the start in our conversation. strategy_text: As of the time of me writing this article, I’ve been a professional relationship coach full time for the past seven years. Why is that? The stigma of online dating users being the social rejects that they may have been in the earrrrrly, early years of online dating simply doesn’t hold weight any longer. I have found attractive, educated, dynamic, amazing people through online dating in major cities in five different countries around the world. I am constantly amazed with the quality of people that I meet through online dating. Again, my hope for you is that I can walk you through this entire process and have the best chance possible to meet your dream partner using online dating as your method. /  / The Biggest Benefits Of Online Dating

strategy_text: I do not like to go to bars and clubs, so I thought I would try online dating.  I look for men who also do not frequent bars and clubs.  Plenty of Fish and Tinder are not really sites where I would look for a long-term relationship.  I have found that the men there are looking for a hook-up or even for online sex or sexting.  Many of them admit to being married or in a relationship and are just bored. / I have hooked up through Tinder after being lonely for a long time.  So if I just want company or someone to chat with sexually I go to Tinder or POF.  I use Match to look for someone who has some things in common with me.  I find a lot and dates are easy to get but I am very picky.  I have gone on a lot of dates and men are NOT at all what they present in their profiles.  It is actually often quite funny. / I still have a lot of hope for Match.  If we chat online and it goes very well I usually agree to a date.  As far as strategy I believe Match makes that very easy.  They do a good job of putting people together who have a lot in common.  One thing I do is look through the newest members for men who don't have as much in common.  That makes for a more interesting conversation and a more interesting date.  After all, opposites attract. /
change_strategy_text: I am much LESS open than I once was when messaging.  I save as much as possible for the actual date.  I think it is sexy to be mysterious.   I also have a few things that are deal breakers so I ask those questions up front.  No use wasting time.
